<p>Georgia has quietly become one of the fastest-growing and most economically dynamic states in the Southeast. Atlanta's Hartsfield-Jackson Airport -- the world's busiest by passenger traffic -- has made Georgia a logistics and distribution powerhouse. The state's film and television production industry has exploded since aggressive tax credits were introduced in 2008, earning Georgia the nickname "Y'allywood" and generating more film production volume than Hollywood itself in some recent years. Atlanta has also emerged as a legitimate technology hub, home to companies like NCR, Mailchimp, and a growing constellation of startups, alongside financial institutions and a massive Fortune 500 presence including Coca-Cola, Delta Air Lines, and UPS.</p>

<p>Georgia converted from a graduated income tax to a flat tax system in 2022, with ongoing rate reductions scheduled through the mid-2020s. This makes Georgia's state income tax simple to calculate: a single percentage applied to taxable income. This generator applies Georgia's current rate and all federal taxes to produce a complete, accurate pay stub PDF.</p>

<h2>Georgia Income Tax Rates</h2>

<p>Georgia switched from a graduated bracket system to a flat income tax in 2022. The flat rate has been on a legislatively mandated reduction schedule:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>2024:</strong> 5.49% flat rate</li>
  <li><strong>2025:</strong> 5.39% (scheduled reduction)</li>
  <li><strong>2026:</strong> Further reductions if revenue triggers are met</li>
  <li>The rate is scheduled to eventually reach 4.99% pending economic conditions</li>
</ul>

<p>This rate trajectory makes Georgia competitive with other Southeastern states. The conversion from a graduated system (which topped out at 5.75%) to a flat system primarily benefited middle and upper-income earners who previously paid higher marginal rates on income above certain thresholds.</p>

<p>Georgia also provides a personal exemption ($2,700 for single filers in 2024) and a standard deduction ($5,400 for single filers) before the flat rate applies, though the mechanics of withholding table calculations apply these automatically. For pay stub estimation purposes, the effective rate on gross pay is slightly below 5.49% for most workers after these adjustments.</p>

<p>Georgia has no local income tax. City of Atlanta employees and workers in Atlanta do not pay any additional city-level income tax, unlike workers in New York City or Philadelphia.</p>

<h2>Does Georgia Require Pay Stubs?</h2>

<p>Georgia does not mandate that private employers provide pay stubs to employees. The Georgia Department of Labor does not have a regulation requiring wage statements with each paycheck. Employers in Georgia are, of course, subject to federal FLSA record-keeping requirements, but the obligation to give those records to employees on a per-pay-period basis does not exist in Georgia state law.</p>

<p>That said, essentially all major Georgia employers do provide pay stubs voluntarily. Delta Air Lines, UPS, Chick-fil-A, and other large Atlanta-area employers all use sophisticated payroll systems that generate electronic wage statements for employees.</p>

<p>For the substantial portion of Georgia's workforce in film production, construction, agriculture, and gig-based work that does not receive formal pay stubs, this generator provides the income documentation needed for housing, loans, and financial applications.</p>

<h2>Pay Stub Requirements in Georgia</h2>

<p>With no state mandate, the content of a Georgia pay stub is governed by federal standards and the expectations of landlords and lenders. A complete Georgia pay stub should include:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Employer name and address</li>
  <li>Employee name and any relevant ID number</li>
  <li>Pay period start and end dates</li>
  <li>Pay date</li>
  <li>Regular hours worked</li>
  <li>Overtime hours (shown separately)</li>
  <li>Gross wages</li>
  <li>Federal income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Georgia state income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Social Security tax (6.2%)</li>
  <li>Medicare tax (1.45%)</li>
  <li>Any voluntary deductions</li>
  <li>Net pay</li>
  <li>Year-to-date totals</li>
</ul>

<h2>Pay Frequency Laws in Georgia</h2>

<p>Georgia Code Section 34-7-2 requires that employers pay wages at least semi-monthly. Both semi-monthly and bi-weekly payment schedules are common in Georgia. The law requires that paydays be established in advance and posted at the worksite, and that wages be paid within 30 days of the end of the period in which they were earned.</p>

<p>Georgia does not have different pay frequency requirements for different types of employees. All non-exempt employees fall under the same semi-monthly minimum requirement. Most large Georgia employers pay bi-weekly (every two weeks), which tends to be operationally simpler and more popular with employees than semi-monthly (which can result in varying amounts per check due to different calendar month lengths).</p>

<h2>Georgia's Industries and Who Needs Pay Stubs</h2>

<p><strong>Film and television production workers:</strong> Georgia's entertainment industry is one of the most active in the world, with shows like "The Walking Dead," "Stranger Things," "Ozark," and dozens of major feature films shot in the Atlanta area. Film industry workers -- crew members, extras, production assistants, drivers, caterers -- are often paid on a day-rate basis and may work for multiple production companies within a single year. Their income documentation can be complex, and many do not receive traditional pay stubs from each production. Generated stubs based on actual earnings from production work are essential for these workers navigating Atlanta's rental market.</p>

<p><strong>Logistics and warehousing workers:</strong> Atlanta's logistics industry, centered on Hartsfield-Jackson Airport and the surrounding distribution networks of UPS, FedEx, Amazon, and dozens of third-party logistics companies, employs tens of thousands. Many warehouse workers, especially those hired through temp agencies, have had multiple employers within a single year. Generating consolidated income documentation is a common need.</p>

<p><strong>Technology workers:</strong> Atlanta's tech scene has grown dramatically. Hire-by-referral and consulting work is common in Atlanta tech -- many developers and engineers work as contractors for multiple clients. Contract tech workers need pay stub documentation for the competitive rental market in neighborhoods like Midtown, Buckhead, and Decatur.</p>

<p><strong>Agricultural workers in rural Georgia:</strong> Georgia is a major agricultural producer -- the leading producer of peanuts and peaches in the United States, and a significant producer of poultry. Farm and poultry processing workers often receive cash wages or payments through small operations that do not have formal payroll systems. These workers need income documentation for banking access, housing, and financial inclusion.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for Georgia Workers</h2>

<h3>Georgia's income tax rate is changing. Which rate should I use for my pay stub?</h3>
<p>Use the rate in effect during the pay period you are documenting. For pay periods in calendar year 2024, use 5.49%. For 2025, use 5.39% (or the rate in effect once officially confirmed). The scheduled reductions are written into Georgia law and have been taking effect as planned. When using this generator, the default Georgia rate reflects the 2024 rate. If you are generating stubs for 2025 dates, manually note the 2025 rate in your records, as the difference ($10,000 gross pay: $549 vs. $539 state tax) may matter for precise documentation.</p>

<h3>I'm a film production worker in Atlanta. How do I handle income from multiple production companies?</h3>
<p>Each production company is technically a separate employer, and ideally you would generate a separate pay stub for each one reflecting the dates and earnings from that production. When submitting pay documentation for an apartment or loan, you can provide stubs from multiple employers covering the same period, along with your total income. Most Atlanta property managers are accustomed to seeing film industry workers with multiple W-2s from different productions and will accept this type of documentation. Be consistent -- each stub's gross pay should match what you actually earned from that employer, which you can verify against your payment records or 1099s.</p>

<h3>Does Georgia have any state disability or paid family leave deductions?</h3>
<p>No. Georgia has no state disability insurance program and no paid family leave funded through employee payroll deductions. Your Georgia pay stub will not show any SDI, PFL, or similar deductions. Workers who need income replacement during disability or family leave must rely on employer-provided programs, private insurance, or federal FMLA (unpaid). Georgia's payroll deductions are state income tax (5.49%) plus federal taxes only.</p>

<h3>I work at Hartsfield-Jackson as a contractor through a staffing agency. How does my pay stub work?</h3>
<p>Your employer of record is the staffing agency, not the airport or the client company. The agency is responsible for withholding Georgia income tax, federal taxes, and FICA from your paychecks and providing you with pay stubs or access to electronic earnings statements. The agency name appears as the employer on your W-2, and the agency's address should appear on your pay stub. If the agency is not providing compliant pay stubs, request them formally in writing. If you are generating supplemental documentation, use the agency's name as employer.</p>

<h3>Georgia's economy is growing fast. Are there tax changes I should watch for?</h3>
<p>Georgia's income tax is scheduled to continue declining, potentially reaching 4.99%. Additionally, the state legislature has discussed additional tax policy changes periodically. For the most current rates, check the Georgia Department of Revenue website before generating stubs for payroll planning purposes. The broader trend in Georgia is toward lower taxes and a more business-friendly environment, which has contributed to the significant corporate relocations (companies moving headquarters from states like California and Illinois to Georgia) that have characterized the past decade.</p>

